article.description:
The 
Bulls snapped a four-game losing streak with a 96-82 victory over
the slumping New Orleans Hornets on Friday night.
article.headline: Bulls end four-game slump, beat sagging Hornets
article.linkText: Bulls end four-game slump, beat sagging Hornets
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- The role was familiar to Ben Gordon. So was the result. The NBA's top sixth man as a rookie last season, Gordon scored 25 points to help the Chicago Bulls snapped a four-game losing streak with a 96-82 victory over the slumping New Orleans Hornets on Friday night. The Bulls (30-39) shook up their starting lineup, overcame a rough first quarter and pulled within 2½ games behind of Philadelphia, which lost to Orlando. Chicago has two games left with the 76ers. "What am I gonna do? Complain about it?" Gordon, who has started 41 games, said of the move to the bench. Gordon scored 10 points in the second quarter, nine in the fourth, and was 9-for-15 from the field. Tyson Chandler grabbed a season-high 21 rebounds, one shy of his career-high. Luol Deng scored 17 points, Othella Harrington added 16, and Kirk Hinrich had 14 points and nine assists. Chris Paul had 13 points and five assists for New Orleans (32-35), which lost for the 10th time in 11 games and trails eighth-place Sacramento by 1 1-2 games in the Western Conference. P.J. Brown added 11 points and nine rebounds. The Hornets shot 6-of-23 in the fourth quarter. "We're just not a very good basketball team right now," coach Byron Scott said. "To me, we have a lot of glaring holes on both ends of the floor. The biggest thing is that we're so weak mentally." It came to a head in the second quarter, when the Bulls scored a season-high 35 points and turned a 28-15 deficit into a 50-46 halftime lead. "They got their confidence back, and we were in a dogfight," Scott said. After New Orleans' David West missed short on a jump shot, Gordon hit a 3-pointer and Hinrich followed with a jumper that increased the Bulls' lead to 81-75 with 5:17 left in the game. After Brown's tip-in, Hinrich hit a 3-pointer to make it 84-77 with 4:38 left and give the Bulls their biggest lead to that point. Michael Sweetney then blocked David West twice down low. And Deng's 3-pointer with 1:47 left made it 91-80. With the losses mounting and time running out, the Bulls shook up their lineup again. Sweetney, Andres Nocioni and Duhon started for Chandler, Gordon and Malik Allen, who has a bad back. Unlike last season, when they overcame an 0-9 start and made the playoffs for the first time since the Michael Jordan-Scottie Pippen championship era, the Bulls have been unable to sustain momentum. A year ago, they were in the process of winning nine straight and 12 of 13. The Bulls' longest win streak this season is four games, and they have used 11 starting lineups. This time, it was Hinrich, Duhon, Deng, Nocioni and Sweetney -- the 10th time they've started together. "If guys are coming off the bench or not, you've got to bring the same kind of energy every night," said Gordon, who scored in single digits in three of the previous four games. "It shouldn't matter if you're starting or not starting. It's good to see that we got a win." At times a forgotten man, Sweetney caught the Bulls' attention with 12 points and nine rebounds in 17:30 during Wednesday's 95-85 loss at Indiana. Coach Scott Skiles hoped the move to the bench would help Gordon rediscover the fourth-quarter touch he showed as a rookie last season. He also considered taking Hinrich out of the starting lineup. Asked if the change helped him, Gordon said, "It doesn't really matter. We got the win. It worked for us today. Hopefully, it'll work the remainder of the season."

Game notes
The Hornets assigned rookie forward Brandon Bass to the Tulsa 66ers of the NBA Development League. Bass is averaging 1.6 points and 1.7 rebounds in 19 games. ... Although the Bulls lack a veteran leader, the odds of them bringing back Antonio Davis appear slim. Davis has a bad back, was released by Toronto on Thursday and would not be eligible for the postseason. Traded with Eddy Curry by the Bulls to New York in October, Davis was suspended for five games for running into the stands after his wife got into a confrontation with a fan in Chicago in January. "I understand he has a back injury," Skiles said before the game. "He wouldn't be playoff-eligible. ... I don't know if it makes sense or not."
